    "flowchart": {
        "name": "Extrude polygons to make steps that go up and down",
        "description": "A example of how to extrude polygons by different heights to make steps that go up and down.\n\nThe key here is to first check if it is an even row or an odd row. This is done with the formula:\n\n    row % 2 == 0\n\nThe % operator retuens the remainder after division. If the remainder of a division by 2 is 0, then it must be even.\n\nFor even rows the heigh is simply i.\n\nFor odd rows, we need to reverse the height, so the first block in the row is the highest, and teh last is the lowest. This is done with the formula:\n\n    height = ( row * 9 ) + ( 8 - ( i % 9 ) )\n\nThe final 'if' condition just reverses the direction when i gets above a certain number.\n",
